The overall spatial distribution of the supply levels of six key ecosystem services on the QTP did not show substantial changes during 2000–2020 (Fig. 3
                        ), but many local changes and an overall increase in supply occurred (Fig. S2). Provisioning services showed a clear spatial pattern of high in the southeast to low in the northwest. WY as a whole shows a decreasing spatial distribution pattern from southeast to northwest. During the period 2000–2020, WY on the QTP in general experienced a significant increase (Table 2
                        ). In terms of spatial changes, the average growth rate of WY in most counties in north-central Tibet and the northeastern QTP was more than 10%. In particular, the number of counties with high-level WY that produced more than 300 mm of water in 2020 exceeded 140 counties. The spatial pattern of FP was relatively stable, and the FP in the Yarlung Zangbo River, Nyangqu River and Lhasa River Basin (YNLB), which is an important agricultural production area in Tibet, was always between 100 and 200 tons/km2 in all counties. FP on the QTP as a whole increased significantly after 2005 (Table 2), and in terms of spatial variation, the eastern part of the plateau saw a larger overall increase in FP, especially in some counties in eastern Qinghai and Sichuan provinces, where the average increase was more than 5%.
